// Regression: two imported modules each define `fn identity<T>` with the
// same signature.  The codegen generic-function registry was keyed by the
// bare name, so the second registration overwrote the first and every
// later call site silently dispatched to whichever body won the race.
//
// Expected behaviour (post-fix): each module-qualified call site routes
// to *its own* defining module's body.
//   `genericlib.identity(1)`     → body in genericlib::identity     (no print)
//   `genericlib_alt.identity(2)` → body in genericlib_alt::identity (prints "alt::identity")
//
// Pre-fix (bug): both call sites would print the same way (either both
// "alt::identity" or neither), because both routed to the single FuncOp
// materialised under the unqualified mangled symbol `identity$int`.
import genericlib;

import genericlib_alt;

fn main() {
    println(genericlib.identity(1));
    println(genericlib_alt.identity(2));
}
